<bibRefCitation author="Smith, M. A." box="[891,1042,1952,1977]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" refId="ref65609" refString="Smith, M. A. (1935) The fauna of British India, including Ceylon and Burma. Reptilia and Amphibia. Vol. II. Sauria. Taylor and Francis, Ltd., Red Lion Court, Fleet Street, London, 440 pp. [Reprint Edition 1974, Today and Tomorrow's Printers and Publishers]" type="book" year="1935">Smith (1935)</bibRefCitation>
to Magas, Sistan and Baluchistan Prov., 
<collectingCountry box="[225,274,1988,2011]" name="Iran" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Iran</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,151,501]" box="[151,560,151,176]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
DISTRIBUTION. SE 
<collectingCountry box="[365,413,152,175]" name="Iran" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Iran</collectingCountry>
, W 
<collectingCountry box="[458,557,151,176]" name="Pakistan" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,151,501]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
DISTRIBUTION IN 
<collectingCountry box="[348,405,188,211]" name="Iran" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">IRAN</collectingCountry>
. 
<figureCitation box="[419,500,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 74–79. 74" captionStartId="84.[151,264,1557,1580]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,213,1516]" captionTargetId="figure-64@84.[151,1436,193,1536]" captionTargetPageId="84" captionText="FIGURES 74–79. 74. Acanthodactylus khamirensis. 75. Acanthodactylus micropholis. 76. Acanthodactylus nilsoni. 77. Acanthodactylus schmidti. 78. Apathya cappadocica. Blue square denotes the type locality for A. c. urmiana. 79. Apathya yassujica." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4929744" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4929744/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 75</figureCitation>
. Sistan and Baluchistan, 
<collectingRegion box="[779,978,188,212]" country="Iran" name="Hormozgan" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Hormozgan Prov.</collectingRegion>
So far only a single record from 
<collectingRegion country="Iran" name="Kerman" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Kerman Prov.</collectingRegion>
(specimen deposited in the 
<collectingRegion box="[538,617,223,248]" country="Iran" name="Tehran" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Tehran</collectingRegion>
museum, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Anderson, S. C." box="[783,986,223,248]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" refId="ref45318" refString="Anderson, S. C. (1999) The lizards of Iran. Society for the Study of Amphibians and Reptiles, Oxford, Ohio, 442 pp." type="book" year="1999">Anderson (1999))</bibRefCitation>
has been published. Nevertheless, it is very likely that the species distribution spans across this province continuously. Recently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Kamali, K." box="[1159,1336,260,285]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="272 - 273" refId="ref55276" refString="Kamali, K. (2013 b) Geographic distributoin: Acanthodactylus micropholis (Persian Fringe-toed Lizard). Herpetological Review, 44, 272 - 273." type="journal article" year="2013">Kamali (2013b)</bibRefCitation>
reported the first record of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blanford" authorityYear="1874" box="[354,519,295,320]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Acanthodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="micropholis">
<emphasis box="[354,519,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">A. micropholis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[588,748,295,320]" country="Iran" name="Bushehr" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Bushehr Prov.</collectingRegion>
situated 
<quantity box="[849,934,295,320]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" unit="km" value="480.0">480 km</quantity>
W of the previously confirmed westernmost locality.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,151,501]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
HABITAT. Unlike most other members of the genus confined to sand, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blanford" authorityYear="1874" box="[956,1124,367,392]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Acanthodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="micropholis">
<emphasis box="[956,1124,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">A. micropholis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in 
<collectingCountry box="[1193,1238,368,391]" name="Iran" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Iran</collectingCountry>
mostly found on gravel or hard soil substrate with scattered shrubby vegetation. On the other hand, Pakistani populations inhabit sandy stream beds and canyons (
<bibRefCitation author="Minton, S. A." box="[517,667,439,464]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="27 - 184" refId="ref59265" refString="Minton, S. A. (1966) A contribution to the herpetology of West Pakistan. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 134, 27 - 184. http: // hdl. handle. net / 2246 / 1129" type="journal article" year="1966">Minton 1966</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Khan, M. S." box="[679,808,439,464]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" refId="ref56151" refString="Khan, M. S. (2006) Amphibians and Reptiles of Pakistan. Krieger Publishing Company, Malabar, Florida, 311 pp." type="book" year="2006">Khan 2006</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
